\section{Parallax}
\emph{By M. Salem}
\begin{figure}[tb]
\center
\includegraphics[width=0.9\linewidth]{parallaxstar1.png}
\caption{\small An illustration of Parallax. The foreground (nearby) star appears to shift positions when observed six months apart (in July and January). By measuring the full angle and dividing by 2, you can get the parallax angle, p. Using some trigonometry, since we know the distance from the Earth to the Sun, you can calculate the distance to the star (d).}
\label{parallax}
\end{figure}

\paragraph{}
Distance to objects in space is a very important piece of information in astronomy. Unfortunately, it's also very hard to obtain. We start the semester with a very simple method, used for the closest stars in our solar neighborhood: Parallax.
\paragraph{}
As the Earth orbits the Sun, the position of nearby stars, with respect to far away background stars, appears to shift. Measuring the total angle of shift can give us a measure of distance to the nearby star. This is the parallax method, illustrated in Figure \ref{parallax}.  We'll use this method to find the distance to two different stars.

\begin{figure}[t]
\center
\includegraphics[width=0.9\linewidth]{stars.png}
\caption{\small Motion of two stars due to parallax. Two images are taken of the same region of the sky, 6 months apart. These are superimposed on top of each other and show that the apparent position of star A and star B has moved, relative to everything else (the background stars).}
\label{star}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Distance to a star}

\paragraph{}
Figure \ref{star} shows two stars in the same field observed 6 months apart.  We combined two images so you could see the shift the stars made in this time. Astronomers often use different units than degrees to describe an angle, since many times 1 degree is very large compared to the angular size of a given object. Astronomers often use arcseconds or arcminutes instead of degrees. There are 60 arcminutes in a degree, and 60 arcseconds in an arcminute. The scale in the upper right corner represents an angle of 0.1 arcseconds, written as 0.1'' (not 0.1 inches). 
\paragraph{}
In this section we will use a unit of measure called a parsec (pc).  A star 1 pc from the Sun will have a parallax angle of 1''.  In our equation for parallax, if we convert the parallax angle to arcseconds and the distances to pc, we find that $\theta=\frac{1}{d}$.  But remember!  For this form of the equation to hold, $\theta$ must be in arcseconds and d must be in pc.
\begin{enumerate}
\item What is the total angular shift for each star over this time period?  
\item What is the parallax angle for each star?  
\item What is the distance to each star, in parsecs?
\item We can measure parallax angles up to about 0.005 arcseconds.  What is the maximum distance we can use parallax to determine distances?  
\item Our galaxy is about 30 kpc in diameter.  What fraction of the galaxy's diameter can we measure distances out to using parallax?
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Rooftop Parallax}

\paragraph{}
Our goal is to measure the distance from Pupin to a tower of Union Theological Seminary, across the street.
\begin{enumerate}
\item We need an instrument that measures angular sizes. Take an index card and cut a horizontal slot through the bottom of the card so it can be slid onto a meter stick.  On the top of the card cut a 1 cm wide notch.
\item Next go up to the roof. Before we make any measurements, what order of magnitude is the distance to the tower (with units)?
\item I'll show you where to stand. For consistency we will measure the distance to the back, left spire on Union's tower. You will notice that there is a building across the river in New Jersey that is behind this spire. As you walk back and forth along the railing you will see the spire shift position with respect to this background building.
\item To begin, we must measure the angular size of the building in Jersey. This is what you need your meter stick for. Stand somewhere where you can see the entire building. Slide the notched index card onto the meter stick and hold the zero end up to your eye, pointing the other end toward the building.  Slide the card along the meter stick until the building fills the notch. Record the position of the card on the meter stick in your lab notebook.
\item Now stand so that one edge of the spire is aligned with one side of the building.  Have one of your partners mark your position.  Next, walk along the railing until the same spire edge is aligned with the other side of the building.  Have your partner measure the distance between your two observation points.
\item Down in the classroom, use your first measurement to calculate the angular size of the building. 
\item What is the parallax angle in degrees? Now determine the distance to the seminary spire in meters. Does it agree with your order of magnitude estimate?
\item Comment on the sources of uncertainty in your measurements.  What sources will affect the accuracy of your measurement and what sources will affect its precision? 
\item According to google maps, the distance is about 150m.  What is the percent error in your measurement? The uncertainty in the google maps measurement is about 30 m. Does your answer fall within 30m of google maps answer? (\textbf{Note}: It does not have to. Don't change your answer if it is not. If you are outside this range, why do you think this happened?).
\end{enumerate}

